In 2010, the proportion of hatched males tended to be greater for early (57.95%) than for late (48.66%) chicks (GLM; 
   z = −1.90, 
   P = 0.06, 
   N = 419; 
   Fig. 2). Also in 2010, we found that chick sex ratio did not vary between hatching and fledging (which included the austral winter period), both in early (–5.90%; Proportion test; 
   P = 0.47, 
   N = 195/73) and late (+1.34%; 
   P = 1, 
   N = 224/6) chicks (see 
   Fig. 2).

From 2004 to 2009, the mean annual laying date of early breeders did not affect annual sex ratio at fledging (GLM; 
    z = −0.02, 
    P = 0.99). Similarly, the mean annual breeding success of the colony over the 10-year study (2000–2009) was not related to fledgling sex ratio (GLM; 
    z = 1.07, 
    P = 0.28).
